Logs.

Docker logs reads what a container's main process wrote to standard output and standard error. The key flags shape what slice you see. Plain docker logs prints everything since the container started. The follow flag streams new output as it arrives, like a live tail. The tail flag limits you to the last so-many lines. The since and until flags window the output by time, accepting durations or timestamps. And the timestamp flag prefixes each line with the daemon's clock.

It helps to know where these logs actually live. The daemon writes them through whatever logging driver is active, and the default driver, j-son-file, stores them in a file under slash var slash lib slash docker. Other drivers ship logs elsewhere entirely, to the system journal, to sys-log, or off to a cloud logging service. You set the driver globally in the daemon configuration or per-container with a log-driver flag, and that is covered in notebook ten. The thing to remember now is that docker logs only works for the j-son-file and journal-d drivers. Switch to another driver and you read your logs from that destination instead.

Two gotchas catch nearly everyone. The first is buffered output. Many runtimes, python especially, buffer their standard output when it is not a terminal, so your prints can take a long time to show up in docker logs. The fix is to set the unbuffered environment variable or run python with the unbuffered flag. The second is disk fill. The j-son-file driver grows without bound unless you configure rotation, so a chatty container can fill your disk in hours. Set a max size and a max file count in the daemon configuration to cap it.
